b'' b'| does anyone out there know of a way to have a unix machine automatically' b"| set it's display variable to that of the xterm you're using when it's" b"| not the machine that's serving you x?" b'|' b"| the best i've been able to come up with has been a rather convoluted" b'| script that extracts your ip from the whos command, and it' b'| frequently fails, not to mention that it requires having your user' b'| name added to it.' b'|' b'| andrew inman, consultant, itd consulting and support services' b'|' b'|' b'from my own notes on this subject....' b'' b'methods to automatically passwd authorization from one machine to another.' b'this also includes the problem of notifing the remote host of the current' b'display that is being used.' b'' b'1/ use rsh/rexec/on... (the method in the xauth manual)' b'set up the your .rhosts file in the home directory on the remote' b'machine so that a password in not required to remotly execute commands.' b'' b'xauth extract $display rsh other xauth merge b'' b'this method is also used by xrsh to pass authorization. my vampire' b'program also uses a variation, however i wrap it as part of the remote' b'command sequence (eg: xauth add $auth)' b'' b"included in this method is the use of `xrlogin' and `xrsh' to do" b'this job for you. these programs usally (the newer ones that is) allow' b'you to pass a secified list of environment variables which includes' b"the `display' and/or a copy of the authorization code required." b'' b"the `xon' program available (if enabled) on sun machines will also" b'pass environment variables, as well as the current directory. you will' b'however be required to store the authority in such a variable for' b'passing. unless you are also have shared home directories.' b'' b'warning: environment variables and command line arguments are visible' b"in `ps' listing with the appropiate flags. as such passing authorization" b'information in environment variables or as arguments is not recomended.' b'the recommended method as given in the manual (shown above) is safe from' b'the view of other users.' b'' b'2/ wrap it as part of the term environment variable.' b'this method uses the fact that most remote command executors do pass' b'the term environment variable to the remote host. it is then a matter of' b'an appropiate script in your remote .login file to extract the information' b'from the term environment variable and set up things appropiatly.' b'a version of the xrlogin script is available on the network which does' b'this. basically you change the term environment variable before the' b'actual call to rlogin is performed, to include your display and your' b'authorization.' b'on the remote machine you then extract this information and return the' b'term environment variable to normal before you use it for reseting or' b"stty'ing your terminal." b'' b'---8<---' b'script for launching rlogin:' b'#!/bin/sh' b'# ~/bin/rl rlogin with display:' b'if -n "$display" then' b'case "$display" in' b':*) display=`hostname`$display b'esac' b'term="$term&$display&`xauth nextract $display`"' b'export term' b'fi' b'rlogin b'---8<---' b'add to your .cshrc or .login' b'if $?term then' b"if `echo $term tr -cd then" b'echo "$term" cut \'-d&\' -f3 xauth nmerge b'setenv display `echo "$term" cut \'-d&\' -f2`' b'setenv term `echo "$term" cut \'-d&\' -f1`' b'endif' b'endif' b'---8<---' b'xterm command to use' b'xterm -t hostname -e ~/bin/rl hostname' b'---8<---' b'' b'3/ nfs.' b'write it to a file on a shared nfs partition you have access to.' b'note that if the home directories are nfs mounted, then authorization' b'is automatically passed, hoever you will still have to pass your' b'display environment variable via a file or other means. ie:' b'' b'login host: echo $display ~/.x11host' b'remote host: setenv display `cat ~/.x11host`' b'' b'4/ finger for the info in a .plan file' b"this involves encrypting the information into your `.plan' or" b"`.project' and having the remote machine finger for the information." b'this has the disadvantage of having the information to anyone fingering' b'the user. thus requiring a encryption method that is uniq to each' b'individual. ie: the method of decyrption must not be shared or known' b'by others, nor should it be easy to determine.' b"a improvment is to use the `who fingered me' technique to only give" b'the information only to your own remote accounts and not just to anyone' b'who is asking.' b'this last method was developed last year by a second year here, untill' b'i explained to him the need for the encryption, at which point he gave' b'up this method. it is however a valid method. it is easer than but' b'less secure.' b'' b'' b'------------------------------------------------------------------------------' b'"magic is real unless declared an integer" john p.melvin' b'------------------------------------------------------------------------------' 